  "prompt": "What's the best way to calculate percentage off of something?",
  "response": "To calculate the percentage off of something, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Identify the Original Price:** Determine the original price of the item.\n\n2. **Determine the Discount Percentage:** Identify the percentage discount being offered.\n\n3. **Calculate the Discount Amount:**\n   - Use the formula:\n     \\[\n     \\text{Discount Amount} = \\text{Original Price} \\times \\left(\\frac{\\text{Discount Percentage}}{100}\\right)\n     \\]\n\n4. **Calculate the New Price:**\n   - Subtract the discount amount from the original price:\n     \\[\n     \\text{New Price} = \\text{Original Price} - \\text{Discount Amount}\n     \\]\n\n### Example:\nLet's say the original price of an item is $50, and the discount percentage is 20%.\n\n1. **Original Price:** $50\n2. **Discount Percentage:** 20%\n3. **Calculate the Discount Amount:**\n   \\[\n   \\text{Discount Amount} = 50 \\times \\left(\\frac{20}{100}\\right) = 50 \\times 0.20 = 10\n   \\]\n4. **Calculate the New Price:**\n   \\[\n   \\text{New Price} = 50 - 10 = 40\n   \\]\n\nThus, the new price after a 20% discount would be $40.",
